> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-5\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">5.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-5\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Ibid.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-6\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">6.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-6\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Ibid.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-7\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">7.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-7\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Flood Construction Levels and Setbacks for Farm Building Situations. British Columbia Ministry of Agriculture, July 2008, pp. 2. <a href=\"https://www2.gov.bc.ca/assets/gov/farming-natural-resources-and-industry/agriculture-and-seafood/farm-management/structures-and-mechanization/823400-2_flood_const_levels_and_setbacks.pdf\">https://www2.gov.bc.ca/assets/gov/farming-natural-resources-and-industry/agriculture-and-seafood/farm-management/structures-and-mechanization/823400-2_flood_const_levels_and_setbacks.pdf</a>.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-8\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">8.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-8\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Ibid, 2.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-9\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">9.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-9\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Ibid, 3-4.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-10\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">10.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-10\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Ibid, 5.</p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-11\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">11.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-11\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  FEMA (n.d) Chapter 7 dry floodproofing. Retrieve from <a href=\"https://www.fema.gov/media-library-data/20130726-1608-20490-9182/fema_551_ch_07.pdf\">https://www.fema.gov/media-library-data/20130726-1608-20490-9182/fema_551_ch_07.pdf</a></p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-12\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">12.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-12\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  FEMA (n.d). Dry Floodproofing Measures. <a href=\"https://www.fema.gov/media-library-data/06dabddadc3887f91906172d863749ab/P-936_sec3_508.pdf\">https://www.fema.gov/media-library-data/06dabddadc3887f91906172d863749ab/P-936_sec3_508.pdf</a></p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n<!-- Images -->\n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-i1\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">i1.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-i1\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Figure 1. FEMA (n.d) Chapter 7 dry floodproofing. Retrieve from <a href=\"https://www.fema.gov/media-library-data/20130726-1608-20490-9182/fema_551_ch_07.pdf\">https://www.fema.gov/media-library-data/20130726-1608-20490-9182/fema_551_ch_07.pdf</a></p>\n      </li>\n      <br/> <br/>\n    \n\n    <li class=\"footnote-list-item\" id=\"fn-i2\" style=\"display:inline\">\n          <span class=\"footnote-marker-text\" style=\"display: inline\">i2.</span>\n        \n      <a href=\"#fnref-i2\" class=\"footnote-backref\" style=\"display:undefined;\">\n        ↑\n      </a>\n    <p>  Figure 2. Wikimedian Commonsé (2020). File:Hamburg, HafenCity, Bebauung am Sandtorkai -- 2016 -- 3036.jpg</p>\n      </li>\n      \n    </ol></div>","id":"8043b7a4-55d4-52a5-b9db-5b8a3e6c4bf6","frontmatter":{"date":"October 23, 2020","strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Dry Floodproofing"}},"allMarkdownRemark":{"edges":[{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/amphibious-buildings/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Amphibious Buildings"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/barrier-islands/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Barrier Islands"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/beach-nourishment/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Beach Nourishment"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/breakwaters/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Breakwaters"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/coastal-wetlands/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Coastal Wetlands"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/development-permits/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Development Permits"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/development-transfers/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Development Transfers"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dikes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Dikes"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dry-floodproofing/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Dry Floodproofing"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dune-building-restoration/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Dune Building / Restoration"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/easement-and-covenants/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Easement and Covenants"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/emergency-planning-and-preparedness/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Emergency Planning Preparedness"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/evacuation-routes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Evacuation Routes"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/floodwalls/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Floodwalls"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/foreshore-tenure/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Foreshore Tenure"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/groynes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Groynes"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/land-acquisition/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Land Acquisition"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/land-trust/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Land Trust"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/protected-area-zoning/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Protected Area Zoning"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/reef-systems/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Reef Systems"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/scour-protection/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Scour Protection"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/seawall/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Seawall"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/secondary-dikes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Secondary Dikes"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Storm Surge Barriers"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/subdivision-regulation-and-development-control/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Subdivision Regulation and Development Control"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/warning-system/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Warning System"}}},{"node":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/wet-floodproofing/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Wet Floodproofing"}}}]}},"pageContext":{"animationSlug":"//strategies/dry-floodproofing/animation.*png/","slug":"/strategies/dry-floodproofing/","foo":"bar","subpages":{"benefits":"<ul>\n<li>Builds resilience by providing a secondary means of protection to dikes</li>\n<li>Improves flood protection when other measures are difficult to implement due to space constraints </li>\n<li>Less costly when compared to other methods of flood retrofitting</li>\n<li>The implementation does not require additional land space <sup id=\"fnref-11\"><a href=\"#fn-11\" class=\"footnote-ref\">11</a></sup></li>\n<li>Can be used to bring non-residential structures into compliance with floodplain management regulations and codes <sup id=\"fnref-12\"><a href=\"#fn-12\" class=\"footnote-ref\">12</a></sup></li>\n</ul>","challenges":"<ul>\n<li>Will not minimize the impacts of high-velocity water flow and wave action on a building or structure <sup id=\"fnref-11\"><a href=\"#fn-11\" class=\"footnote-ref\">11</a></sup></li>\n<li>May be difficult to apply to existing buildings and infrastructure</li>\n<li>May not always lead to an improvement in flood mitigation that aligns with existing floodplain management bylaws <sup id=\"fnref-11\"><a href=\"#fn-11\" class=\"footnote-ref\">11</a></sup></li>\n<li>May fail, if flooding exceeds the level of flood protection intervention </li>\n</ul>","examples":["<h3>Farm Building FCL’s and Setbacks</h3>\n<h4>BC, Canada</h4>\n<p>Dry floodproofing can also be in the form of defining flood construction levels (FCLs) and setbacks for new development. The government of British Columbia and the Ministry of Agriculture provide guidelines on the application of flood construction levels and floodplain setbacks.<sup id=\"fnref-7\"><a href=\"#fn-7\" class=\"footnote-ref\">7</a></sup> In British Columbia, FCLs are used to protect living spaces, electrical and mechanical services from the impact of floodwaters above.<sup id=\"fnref-8\"><a href=\"#fn-8\" class=\"footnote-ref\">8</a></sup> FCLs and setbacks are generally established in some locations but in some cases, they are defined by the elevation above a natural boundary such as a water source.<sup id=\"fnref-9\"><a href=\"#fn-9\" class=\"footnote-ref\">9</a></sup> Additionally, FCLs and setbacks can also be associated with land use, specifically for the location of farm buildings based on building type and size.<sup id=\"fnref-10\"><a href=\"#fn-10\" class=\"footnote-ref\">10</a></sup></p>","<h3>HafenCity</h3>\n<h4>Hamburg, Germany</h4>\n<p>HafenCity is an example of flood adaptation as an alternative to dike construction. The town wanted to retain the beautiful sightlines down to the water, therefore, a dike was not the best option.<sup id=\"fnref-4\"><a href=\"#fn-4\" class=\"footnote-ref\">4</a></sup> Instead, all new buildings were raised on plinths 8 to 9 meters above sea level.<sup id=\"fnref-5\"><a href=\"#fn-5\" class=\"footnote-ref\">5</a></sup> Plinths are artificial mounds that are built using compacted fill, and the interior function as spaces for underground parking. In addition to raising buildings, the roads and bridges of HafenCity are also built roughly eight (8) meters above sea level, therefore allowing the town to function seamlessly during a storm surge.<sup id=\"fnref-6\"><a href=\"#fn-6\" class=\"footnote-ref\">6</a></sup></p>"],"images":["<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 556px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/c464215bc2c78b8ae2199412a77f8786/96638/Figure2.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 68.24324324324324%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/c464215bc2c78b8ae2199412a77f8786/96638/Figure2.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/c464215bc2c78b8ae2199412a77f8786/12f09/Figure2.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/c464215bc2c78b8ae2199412a77f8786/e4a3f/Figure2.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/c464215bc2c78b8ae2199412a77f8786/96638/Figure2.png 556w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 556px) 100vw, 556px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nHafen city Hamburg, Germany  <sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup></p>","<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/4d07a31f8b15df0da5d7bcdb321e043b/8ae3e/Figure1.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 44.5945945945946%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/4d07a31f8b15df0da5d7bcdb321e043b/fcda8/Figure1.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/4d07a31f8b15df0da5d7bcdb321e043b/12f09/Figure1.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/4d07a31f8b15df0da5d7bcdb321e043b/e4a3f/Figure1.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/4d07a31f8b15df0da5d7bcdb321e043b/fcda8/Figure1.png 590w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/4d07a31f8b15df0da5d7bcdb321e043b/8ae3e/Figure1.png 756w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nTypical dry floodproofing building <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>"],"types":"<ul>\n<li><strong>Continuous impermeable walls</strong> include sealing the exterior walls of a building, utilizing waterproof membranes that are impermeable and that have the potential to strengthen the walls.  </li>\n<li><strong>Flood resistant interior core areas</strong> include important components and areas of a building that are made flood-resistant instead of dry proofing the entire footprint of the building.  </li>\n<li><strong>Flood shields</strong> are watertight structures that close any opening in a building’s exterior walls to prevent the entry of floodwater. <sup id=\"fnref-12\"><a href=\"#fn-12\" class=\"footnote-ref\">12</a></sup></li>\n<li><strong>Internal drainage systems</strong> are used to remove water that might seep into a building through fissures or other openings that comprise a flood protection system.</li>\n</ul>","summary":"<p>Dry floodproofing is a practice of utilizing waterproof membranes and other types of sealants to prevent floodwater from entering a building.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> It may also include the installation of watertight seals over windows and doors, diversion of water using berms and mounds, or the establishment of minimum setback regulations for building construction. <sup id=\"fnref-3\"><a href=\"#fn-3\" class=\"footnote-ref\">3</a></sup> <sup id=\"fnref-5\"><a href=\"#fn-5\" class=\"footnote-ref\">5</a></sup> <sup id=\"fnref-6\"><a href=\"#fn-6\" class=\"footnote-ref\">6</a></sup> <sup id=\"fnref-7\"><a href=\"#fn-7\" class=\"footnote-ref\">7</a></sup> <sup id=\"fnref-11\"><a href=\"#fn-11\" class=\"footnote-ref\">11</a></sup> The work required to dry flood-proof a structure could be determined through a risk assessment following local government requirements, guidelines, or policies.<sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup> <sup id=\"fnref-3\"><a href=\"#fn-3\" class=\"footnote-ref\">3</a></sup> Depending on the complexity of the requirements, dry floodproofing is usually a cost-effective retrofit. Dry floodproofing contributes to a reduction in potential flood damage by decreasing the probability of inundation to the interior of a building. Dry floodproofing is a useful alternative as a flood mitigation measure where the relocation or elevation of a building is not a plausible cost-effective or technically feasible alternative. <sup id=\"fnref-12\"><a href=\"#fn-12\" class=\"footnote-ref\">12</a></sup></p>"},"previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/challenges/"},"html":"<ul>\n<li>High construction and maintenance cost </li>\n<li>Affects nearby environments and transfers risk onto nearby properties and communities</li>\n<li>May negatively affect water quality in the bay area </li>\n<li>Mostly suitable for locations where inlets and narrow river mouths can be closed <sup id=\"fnref-13\"><a href=\"#fn-13\" class=\"footnote-ref\">13</a></sup> <sup id=\"fnref-14\"><a href=\"#fn-14\" class=\"footnote-ref\">14</a></sup></li>\n</ul>","frontmatter":{"title":""}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/subdivision-regulation-and-development-control/summary/"},"html":"<p>A subdivision regulation is a planning tool that can be used to establish conditions for the protection against environmental hazards, e.g., coastal hazards related to sea-level rise.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> A subdivision is defined as a separate title of land (bare land strata lot, strata unit, townhouse, row house, or a condominium unit).<sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup> The tool works in conjunction with zoning where the administrative responsibility of the subdivision of land is usually given to an Approving Officer who has the power to refuse or approve a subdivision plan.<sup id=\"fnref-3\"><a href=\"#fn-3\" class=\"footnote-ref\">3</a></sup> Subdivision regulation can be complementary to other development control measures. For example, development agreements may require a development to conform to design criteria to ensure public safety. Additionally, development agreements may require developers to demonstrate that a project is not harmful to ecologically sensitive areas.<sup id=\"fnref-5\"><a href=\"#fn-5\" class=\"footnote-ref\">5</a></sup></p>","frontmatter":{"title":""}}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3000541721"]}